---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Research"
  description="Research questions by Hexin Yu on aviation delay propagation, hub and regional airport performance, network resilience, GIS, and transportation systems."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <header class="container page-intro">
      <p class="page-kicker">Research</p>
      <h1>Questions for reading aviation systems through data and geography</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        I frame research as a set of working questions: where do disruptions begin, how do they travel,
        and how can maps make aviation networks easier to reason about?
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="container research-list" aria-label="Research questions">
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">01</p>
        <h2>How do hub airports absorb or amplify disruption?</h2>
        <p>
          Hub airports concentrate aircraft, crews, passengers, and connecting itineraries. I want to compare
          when that concentration creates recovery capacity and when it turns one operational problem into a
          broader network delay.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">02</p>
        <h2>Why do regional airports experience delays differently?</h2>
        <p>
          Regional airports may have fewer alternate flights, smaller buffers, and stronger dependence on inbound
          aircraft. A small delay count can still mean a large reliability problem for passengers and local access.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">03</p>
        <h2>How does delay propagate across airline networks?</h2>
        <p>
          Flight delays are tied to aircraft rotations, airport congestion, crew schedules, and downstream routes.
          I am interested in visual and statistical methods that make these dependencies visible without
          overstating what public data can explain.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">04</p>
        <h2>What makes an aviation network resilient?</h2>
        <p>
          Resilience depends on route redundancy, geography, airport capacity, carrier strategy, and recovery time.
          I want to study how these factors shape the ability of an airport or route system to return to normal.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">05</p>
        <h2>How can GIS make transportation systems more legible?</h2>
        <p>
          Maps can connect route networks, airport regions, delay patterns, and access questions. The challenge is
          to design visualizations that support interpretation instead of turning complex systems into decoration.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="question-number">06</p>
        <h2>What should live aviation tools communicate first?</h2>
        <p>
          Future work may connect live flight status, historical reliability, weather context, and network structure.
          The goal is lightweight decision support for route risk exploration, not a black-box prediction score.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .research-list {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0;
  }

  .research-list article {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 72px minmax(220px, 0.44fr) minmax(0, 0.56fr);
    gap: 28px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72), transparent);
    padding: 28px 0;
  }

  .question-number {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace;
    font-weight: 800;
  }

  .research-list p {
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .research-list article {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 10px;
    }
  }
</style>
